80":"circa 1380","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","ABT 1370":"circa 1370","1337":"1337","1458":"1458","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1444":"1444","about 1438":"circa 1438","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","about 1410":"circa 1410","1427":"1427","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England., United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1380–1443":"about 1380–1443","1365–1427":"1365–1427","1366–Female":"1366–Deceased","1380–1443":"1380–1443","1365–1444":"1365–1444","1410–1458":"1410–1458","–Female":"Deceased","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1346–1400":"1346–1400","about 1380":"about 1380","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","ABT 1370":"about 1370","1337":"1337","1458":"1458","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1444":"1444","about 1438":"about 1438","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","about 1410":"about 1410","1427":"1427","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England., United Kingdom":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Trenoweth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Cornish: locative name from one or more of at least twenty places in Cornwall named with Cornish  <i>tre</i> ‘house, settlement’ +  <i>nowyth</i> ‘new’, with the spellings  <i>Trenewth</i>,  <i>Trenouth</i>,  <i>Trenowah</i>,  <i>Trenower</i>,  <i>Trenoweth</i>,  <i>Trenowth</i>,  <i>Trenute</i>, or  <i>Trenuth</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Trenouth","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trenoweth  ."]},{"name":"Trenwith","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trenoweth  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Trenoweth was born about 1380, in Cornwall, England, her father, John Trenoweth, was 44 and her mother, Joan Treiago, was 36. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with John Trethurffe MP. She died in 1443, in Philleigh, Cornwall, England, at the age of 64."},"et":{"about 1380–1443":"umbes 1380–1443","1365–1427":"1365–1427","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1380–1443":"1380–1443","1365–1444":"1365–1444","1410–1458":"1410–1458","–Female":"Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1346–1400":"1346–1400","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","ABT 1370":"umbes 1370","1337":"1337","1458":"1458","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1444":"1444","about 1438":"umbes 1438","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1427":"1427","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England., United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1380–1443":"noin 1380–1443","1365–1427":"1365–1427","1366–Female":"1366–Kuollut","1380–1443":"1380–1443","1365–1444":"1365–1444","1410–1458":"1410–1458","–Female":"Kuollut","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1346–1400":"1346–1400","about 1380":"noin 1380","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","ABT 1370":"noin 1370","1337":"1337","1458":"1458","1346":"1346","1400":"1400","1444":"1444","about 1438":"noin 1438","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","about 1410":"noin 1410","1427":"1427","Trethurfe, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Trenoweth, Cornwall, England., United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1380–1443":"environ 1380–1443","1365–1427":"1365–1427","1366–